    <div class="content-body__right">
        <p>
            One way to gauge the sustainability of federal finances is to observe how the federal debt has changed over time. The U.S. has experienced a deficit in each year since 2001, with a spike from 2009 to 2012 because of the financial crisis and ensuing recession.
        </p>
        <section class="accordion">
            <h1 class="accordion__heading">What is surplus?</h1>
            <div class="accordion__content">
                <div id="surplusComponent">
                    <div class="deficit--surplus__surplus">
                        A surplus occurs when the government collects more money than it spends.
                    </div>
                    <div class="deficit--surplus__balanced">
                        A balanced budget occurs when the government spends as much as it collects.
                    </div>
                    <div class="deficit--surplus__deficit">
                        A deficit occurs when the government collects less money than it spends.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
        <section class="accordion">
            <h1 class="accordion__heading">What is sustainable policy?</h1>
            <div class="accordion__content">
                <p>According to the <a href="https://www.fiscal.treasury.gov/reports-statements/financial-report/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Financial Report of the United States Government (FR)</a> government spending is considered to be sustainable when deficit spending as a percentage of gross domestic product is steady or declining.</p>
            </div>
        </section>
